TITLE: Handling API Calls Safely with Sessions
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates proper and improper ways to handle asynchronous API calls when using sessions. Always await or return async API calls to avoid race conditions.
SOURCE: https://github.com/feathers-studio/telegraf-docs/blob/master/guide/session.md#2025-04-19_snippet_3

LANGUAGE: TypeScript
CODE:
```
bot.on("message", async ctx => {
	// ‚ùå BAD! You did not await ctx.reply()
	ctx.reply("Hello there!");

	// ‚úÖ Good, you awaited your requests.
	await ctx.reply("Hello there!");

	// Also applies to any other async calls you may make:
	const res = await fetch(API_URL);

	// Returning calls is also okay, because the promise will be returned
	return ctx.sendAnimation(GOOD_MORNING_GIF);
});
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Session Updates Across Multiple Middlewares
DESCRIPTION: Shows how changes to session data are managed across multiple middlewares. Updates from all middlewares will be persisted when the middleware chain completes.
SOURCE: https://github.com/feathers-studio/telegraf-docs/blob/master/guide/session.md#2025-04-19_snippet_4

LANGUAGE: TypeScript
CODE:
```
bot.use(async (ctx, next) => {
	ctx.session.count++; // increment once
	return next(); // pass control to next middleware
});

bot.on("message", async (ctx, next) => {
	ctx.session.count++; // increment again
});

// all middleware have run. ctx.session will be written back to store
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Session Behavior with Errors in Middleware
DESCRIPTION: Illustrates how session data is still written even when a middleware throws an error. If rollback is needed, errors must be caught and handled explicitly.
SOURCE: https://github.com/feathers-studio/telegraf-docs/blob/master/guide/session.md#2025-04-19_snippet_5

LANGUAGE: TypeScript
CODE:
```
bot.use(async (ctx, next) => {
	ctx.session.count++; // increment count
	await functionThatThrows();
	return next();
});

// incremented count will still be written to store
```

----------------------------------------

TITLE: Avoiding Race Conditions When Updating Session Data
DESCRIPTION: Demonstrates how to properly update session data to avoid race conditions. Warns against using stale values that might have been modified by parallel requests.
SOURCE: https://github.com/feathers-studio/telegraf-docs/blob/master/guide/session.md#2025-04-19_snippet_7

LANGUAGE: TypeScript
CODE:
```
bot.on(message("text"), async ctx => {
	// reading value from session
	const count = ctx.session.count;

	const response = await fetch(API_URL, { body: count });

	// ‚ö†Ô∏è WARNING! You wrote stale value to session.
	// Another request may have updated session while you awaited fetch, be careful of that
	ctx.session.count = count + 1;

	// ‚úÖ Good, you wrote immediately after reading
	ctx.session.count = ctx.session.count + 1;
});
```

